04409nam a22007215i 9780801469688DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)885220599  a(OCoLC)992523683  a97808014696887 a10.7591/97808014696882doi  a(DE-B1597)481919  a(OCoLC)865565852  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE183.8.I6bS56 2016 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a327.730417090342231 aSim, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Union Forever :bThe Irish Question and U.S. Foreign Relations in the Victorian Age /cDavid Sim. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b5 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe United States in the World00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: An Atlantic Triangle -- t1. Challenging the Union: American Repeal and U.S. Diplomacy -- t2. Ireland Is No Longer a Nation: The Irish Famine and American Diplomacy -- t3. Filibusters and Fenians: Contesting Neutrality -- t4. The Fenian Brotherhood, Naturalization, and Expatriation: Irish Americans and Anglo-American Comity -- t5. Toward Home Rule: From the Fenians to Parnell’s Ascendancy -- t6. A Search for Order: The Decline of the Irish Question in American Diplomacy -- tEpilogue: Rapprochement, Paris, and a Free State -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the mid-nineteenth century the Irish question—the governance of the island of Ireland—demanded attention on both sides of the Atlantic. In A Union Forever, David Sim examines how Irish nationalists and their American sympathizers attempted to convince legislators and statesmen to use the burgeoning global influence of the United States to achieve Irish independence. Simultaneously, he tracks how American politicians used the Irish question as means of furthering their own diplomatic and political ends.Combining an innovative transnational methodology with attention to the complexities of American statecraft, Sim rewrites the diplomatic history of this neglected topic. He considers the impact that nonstate actors had on formal affairs between the United States and Britain, finding that not only did Irish nationalists fail to involve the United States in their cause but actually fostered an Anglo-American rapprochement in the final third of the nineteenth century. Their failures led them to seek out new means of promoting Irish self-determination, including an altogether more radical, revolutionary strategy that would alter the course of Irish and British history over the next century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIrish question. 4aEngland. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146968840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469688423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801469688/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK